Fire Damper Checklist [H]
Fire Damper Checklist
Penetration details have been captured
Position damper centrally in penetration aperture as per system drawing with IBS backing rod and temporary supports or packers.
Galvanised steel casing positioned centrally within aperture is 0.7mm or greater gauge

Killargo fire rated mastic has been applied to the gaps between fire damper, casing perimeter & building element on both sides. Gaps between the fire damper and wall no greater than 25mm.Ensure fill depth is 50mm. No evidence of cracking.

0.7mm minimum steel angles at least twice the width of the penetration gap, fixed to damper casing with steel screws, bolts or pip rivets and fixed to wall with steel fixings at maximum 150mm centre spacing or 2 per side for casing lengths up to 250mm or 3 per side for casing lengths 251-400mm
Ductwork is connected to either side of the casing with nylon bolts on the flanges as per the AS1682.2 break away joint method. Bolts do not exceed an 8mm diameter.
Access panel is provided to conveniently access fire damper for visual and/or maintenance inspections.
Fire damper labelling in accordance with AS1682.2 has been placed and clearly identifies the fire damper

Fire Damper Checklist [O]
Fire Damper Checklist
Penetration details have been captured
Does the fire damper mounting frame completely penetrates the wall or slab into which it is installed?

Does the damper mounting frame retained either, on both sides by means of flanges butted against the face of the wall or slab and fixed to the mounting frame or on one side by one flange only, fixed to the wall and damper frame allowing the damper body to expand without distortion to the blades?
Does the penetration for the fire damper have clearance on all sides equal to half the width of the flange used to retain the damper frame?
Is this clearance filled with an approved non-combustible compressible material such as rockwool to the full thickness of the wall or slab involved?

Smoke Damper Checklist [I]
Smoke Damper Checklist
Smoke damper must be placed in the duct work so the closed blades are with 610 mm of the smoke barrier and before any duct inlets or outlets (See photo attached)

When joining or fastening the damper to duct work, dampers shall be fastened with M6 bolts or M5 screws. Fasteners shall be spaced a maximum of 305 mm center to center with a minimum of two fastners per side.

Smoke dampers must be sealed between the damper frames and duct work. The sealant shall be pressed in place to dispel any air and shall be applied to one side of the damper's face. Use the minimum amount of the material to completely seal the joint.
